  "prompt": "What is the magnitude of the force applied by the body on an object due to law of inertia?",
  "response": "The **law of inertia**, also known as **Newton's First Law of Motion**, states that an object will remain at rest or move in a straight line at a constant speed unless acted upon by an external force. Inertia itself is a property of matter that quantifies an object's resistance to changes in its state of motion. It's important to note that **inertia is not a force**, but rather a characteristic of mass.\n\n### Calculating Force Related to Inertia\n\nWhen you want to change the motion of an object (i.e., accelerate it), you need to apply a force. The relationship between force, mass, and acceleration is given by **Newton's Second Law of Motion**, which is mathematically expressed as:\n\n\\[ \\boxed{F = m \\times a} \\]\n\nWhere:\n- **\\( F \\)** is the force applied to the object (in newtons, N).\n- **\\( m \\)** is the mass of the object (in kilograms, kg).\n- **\\( a \\)** is the acceleration produced (in meters per second squared, m/s\u00b2).\n\n### Understanding the Components\n\n1. **Mass (\\( m \\))**: Represents the amount of matter in the object. Greater mass means greater inertia, requiring more force to achieve the same acceleration.\n2. **Acceleration (\\( a \\))**: The rate at which the object's velocity changes. Acceleration can be due to speeding up, slowing down, or changing direction.\n3. **Force (\\( F \\))**: The push or pull applied to the object to change its motion.\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose you have a 10 kg object and you want to accelerate it at \\( 2 \\, \\text{m/s}\u00b2 \\). The force required would be:\n\n\\[ F = 10 \\, \\text{kg} \\times 2 \\, \\text{m/s}\u00b2 = 20 \\, \\text{N} \\]\n\nSo, a force of **20 newtons** is needed to achieve the desired acceleration.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- **Inertia** is a measure of an object's resistance to changes in motion and is directly related to its mass.\n- To **change the motion** of an object, you must apply a force proportional to both its mass and the desired acceleration.\n- The **magnitude of the force** can be calculated using the formula \\( F = m \\times a \\).\n\nIf you have specific values for mass and acceleration, you can plug them into the formula to find the exact force required.",
